member.example:
 Following code shows how to set Run-Time license manually using code and Licensing object.

	public static void Main(string[] args)
	{
		// To obtain your run time key, you need to purchase a license key and then
		// add it in design-time when prompted. Then go to design-time About box 
		// and click the "Get run-time key" link, window with description and your run-time key will popup
		// Once you have the run-time key, then setting it is single line of code
		PureComponents.ScheduleSet.Calendars.Licensing.RunTimeLicenseKey = "YOUR RUNTIME LICENSE KEY GOES HERE";

		// Initialization of your main window goes here, Form1 is the typical sample. Of course it can differ in your case.
		Application.Run(new Form1());
	}


 'Locate constructor of you main (Startup object) Form and enter the following code
 Public Sub New()
		MyBase.New()

		'To obtain your run time key, you need to purchase a license key and then
		'add it in design-time when prompted. Then go to design-time About box
		'and click the "Get run-time key" link, window with description and your run-time key will popup
		'
		'Once you have the run-time key enter it for Licensing object
		PureComponents.ScheduleSet.Calendars.Licensing.RunTimeLicenseKey = "YOUR RUNTIME LICENSE KEY GOES HERE"

		'This call is required by the Windows Form Designer.
		InitializeComponent()

		'Add any initialization after the InitializeComponent() call
		'Your other initialization goes here
	End Sub

member.remarks:

Sizes of src and dest must be equal.

White color results in transparent pixel and black in solid.
            The formula is


            if(sa==255)
            	da = 255 - (sr+sg+sb)/3;
            else	
            	da=0;


